y, Kent, England":"Crayford, Kent, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1438–1470":"1438–1470","1441–1479":"1441–1479","1440–1470":"1440–1470","1465–1539":"1465–1539","1385–1497":"1385–1497","1387–1470":"1387–1470","1385":"1385","1440":"1440","1470":"1470","1458":"1458","1436":"1436","1479":"1479","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1387":"1387","1497":"1497","1441":"1441","1539":"1539","1438":"1438","Little Horsted, Sussex, England":"Little Horsted, Sussex, England","Little Horsted, Wealden, Sussex, England":"Little Horsted, Sussex, England","Crayford, Kent, England":"Crayford, Kent, England","Buxted, Sussex, England":"Buxted, Sussex, England","Buxted, Wealden, Sussex, England":"Buxted, Sussex, England","Crayford, Bexley, Kent, England":"Crayford, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1438–1470":"1438–1470","1441–1479":"1441–1479","1440–1470":"1440–1470","1465–1539":"1465–1539","1385–1497":"1385–1497","1387–1470":"1387–1470","1385":"1385","1440":"1440","1470":"1470","1458":"1458","1436":"1436","1479":"1479","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1387":"1387","1497":"1497","1441":"1441","1539":"1539","1438":"1438","Little Horsted, Sussex, England":"Little Horsted, Sussex, England","Little Horsted, Wealden, Sussex, England":"Little Horsted, Sussex, England","Crayford, Kent, England":"Crayford, Kent, England","Buxted, Sussex, England":"Buxted, Sussex, England","Buxted, Wealden, Sussex, England":"Buxted, Sussex, England","Crayford, Bexley, Kent, England":"Crayford, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pope","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>pope</i> (derived via Old English from Late Latin <i>papa</i> ‘bishop, pope’, from Greek <i>pappas</i> ‘father’, in origin a nursery word.) In the early Christian Church, the Latin term was at first used as a title of respect for male clergy of every rank, but in the Western Church it gradually came to be restricted to bishops, and then only to the bishop of Rome; in the Eastern Church it continued to be used of all priests (see   Popov  ,   Papas  ). The nickname would have been used for a vain or pompous man, or for someone who had played the part of the pope in a pageant or play. The surname is also present in Ireland and Scotland.","North German: variant of   Poppe  .","German: translation of   Pabst  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Popov","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Russian Nikolay, Oleg, Grigoriy, Anatoly, Andrei, Arkadi, Dmitriy, Mikhail, Sergey.  Bulgarian or Macedonian Atanas, Dimitar, Yordan.  Serbian Bosko, Bozidar, Branko.","Russian, Bulgarian, Macedonian, Serbian, and Rusyn: patronymic from <i>pop</i> ‘priest’, from Greek <i>pappas</i> ‘father’ (compare English   Pope  ). The name may sometimes derive from a nickname, but celibacy was not enjoined on priests of the Orthodox Church and so the name can indeed mean ‘son of the priest’. In many cases, however, the Russian name means no more than ‘of the priest’ and designates a servant of a priest. Compare   Popoff  , see also   Pop   2,   Popovic  , and   Popovski   1.","Jewish (American): most likely a shortened form of   Popovski   2. Compare   Popoff  ."]},{"name":"Papke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Bernhard, Erwin, Hans, Otto, Willi.","North German (also <b>Päpke</b>): nickname from a diminutive of Low German <i>pape</i>, Dutch <i>paepe</i> ‘pope’. Compare   Pope  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":17,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Pope was born in 1438, in Little Horsted, Sussex, England, his father, Sir Robert “Poppy” Pope, Esq. of Twyford, was 53 and his mother, Ann Mordox, was 51. He married Joan Weston in 1458, in Crayford, Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1470, in Buxted, Sussex, England, at the age of 32."},"et":{"1438–1470":"1438–1470","1441–1479":"1441–1479","1440–1470":"1440–1470","1465–1539":"1465–1539","1385–1497":"1385–1497","1387–1470":"1387–1470","1385":"1385","1440":"1440","1470":"1470","1458":"1458","1436":"1436","1479":"1479","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1387":"1387","1497":"1497","1441":"1441","1539":"1539","1438":"1438","Little Horsted, Sussex, England":"Little Horsted, Sussex, England","Little Horsted, Wealden, Sussex, England":"Little Horsted, Sussex, England","Crayford, Kent, England":"Crayford, Kent, England","Buxted, Sussex, England":"Buxted, Sussex, England","Buxted, Wealden, Sussex, England":"Buxted, Sussex, England","Crayford, Bexley, Kent, England":"Crayford, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1438–1470":"1438–1470","1441–1479":"1441–1479","1440–1470":"1440–1470","1465–1539":"1465–1539","1385–1497":"1385–1497","1387–1470":"1387–1470","1385":"1385","1440":"1440","1470":"1470","1458":"1458","1436":"1436","1479":"1479","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1387":"1387","1497":"1497","1441":"1441","1539":"1539","1438":"1438","Little Horst